The Minister of Communications and Digital Economy, Dr Isa Ali Ibrahim
Pantami, yesterday, ordered the Nigerian Postal Services (NIPOST) to suspend the
new tariff on registration of courier services in the country. Reacting to complaints by Nigerians on the new hike, Pantami, under whose
purview the supervision of NIPOST falls, took to his Twitter handle to reiterate the position of the Federal Government on the increment. He tweeted: “Our attention has been drawn to an increase in licence fees, which was not part of the regulation I
earlier approved for you. The chairman of NIPOST and the post master general were contacted yesterday to put the
implementation on hold and send a report to our ministry by Monday”. He further clarified that “the power of regulation of NIPOST lies with the
minister, any change of fees must be approved by him. I know the economic challenges of NIPOST. However, looking
at the economic hardship of our citizens, we need to suspend any move.” This directive comes amidst ongoing efforts by the minister to reposition
the postal services sector for optimal efficiency, in line with global best practices and as enshrined in the Universal Postal Union (UPU)global
resolution of September 2019.